AngloGold, Gold Fields, Exxaro, Telkom: South African Stock Market Preview

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-06-13T00:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-13/anglogold-gold-fields-exxaro-telkom-s-africa-stock-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or fall
in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last close.  The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index declined 469.82, or 1.5
percent, to 31,164.35 at the 5 p.m. close on Friday in
Johannesburg.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  : South Africa’s  National
Union of Mineworkers  today begins wage talks with the Chamber of
Mines. The union will seek a wage increase of 14 percent, it
said in an e-mailed statement. The chamber represents Africa’s
largest gold mining companies including AngloGold,  Gold Fields
Ltd. (GFI)   and Harmony Gold Mining Co. Ltd..  AngloGold shares dropped 1.8 percent to 291.05 rand, Gold
Fields fell 1 percent to 98.99 rand while Harmony’s stock rose
0.2 percent to 87.70 rand.  Exxaro Resources Ltd. (EXX)  : The largest coal supplier
to South Africa’s state power utility Eskom Holdings Ltd. on
Friday won a temporary injunction from the Labour Court blocking
a strike planned for Monday, it said in a statement. The
National Union of Mineworkers said it had suspended the strike,
and instructed attorneys to oppose the application for a final
court order. Exxaro shares on Friday fell 80 cents, or 0.5
percent, to 158.54 rand.  John Daniel Holdings Ltd. (JDH)  : The producer of
industrial containers said in a statement that it plans to raise
15 million rand ($2.2 million) in a 7 cents-a-share sale partly
underwritten by its biggest creditor, Escalator Capital Ltd. The
shares were unchanged at 9 cents.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG SJ): Africa’s largest fixed-
line telephone operator publishes earnings statements for the
year ended March. The company expects to report a loss when
compared with a restated profit of 8 billion rand ($1.2 billion)
a year earlier, it said in a statement on May 31. That would be
the company’s first loss since a 2003 initial public offering.
The share lost 3 cents, or 0.1 percent, to 37.05 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
